'''Alamosa photovoltaic power plant''', is an 8.22 MWp [[photovoltaic]] [[power plant]] located in [[San Luis Valley]], Colorado, USA.  The power plant was developed by [[SunEdison]], sells all output to [[Xcel Energy]], and was completed in December 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sunedison.com/press_releases.php?id=14 | title=SunEdison Activates Largest U.S. Photovoltaic Power Plant for Xcel Energy |publisher=SunEdison |date=17 December 2007 |accessdate=13 January 2009}}</ref>

The plant occupies {{convert|83|acre}} of land, and provided enough power to supply 1400 homes in 2008. This made it the largest producer of photovoltaic power in the United States in 2008.  Colorado Xcel customers pay approximately 2% more for electricity to subsidize renewable energy projects.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.denverpost.com/breakingnews/ci_11299138 |title=Alamosa solar plant's success helps prove resource's viability on large scale |publisher=[[The Denver Post]] |date=24 December 2008 |accessdate=13 January 2009 |first=Steve |last=Raabe| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090129193440/http://www.denverpost.com/breakingnews/ci_11299138| archivedate= 29 January 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The plant has received some criticism, saying that the amount of land used is large in comparison to the amount of power generated.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.vaildaily.com/article/20090103/EDITS/901019976/1021&title=Vail%20Daily%27s%20view:%20Smaller%20is%20better%20with%20solar%20energy |title=Vail Daily's view: Smaller is better with solar energy |publisher=Vail Daily |date=3 January 2009 |accessdate=13 January 2009 }}</ref>

